<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910418-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>910418-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Ondaatje Halts Deal   To Invest In, Rejoin   His Former Brokerage</HL><DATE>04/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   T.LOM WNEWS</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SECURITIES (SCR)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)</RE><LP>   TORONTO -- One month after Christopher Ondaatje announcedhe would return to the helm of Loewen Ondaatje McCutcheonInc., one of Canada's largest remaining independent brokeragefirms, the deal has been called off.   No reason was given for the termination. Mr. Ondaatje saidin a statement that he may consider pursuing anothertransaction with Loewen. Neither Mr. Ondaatje nor Loewenexecutives could be reached for comment.</LP><TEXT>   Under the agreement, Mr. Ondaatje was to invest 30 millionCanadian dollars (US$26.1 million) in Loewen Ondaatje inexchange for a 49.7% voting stake and the positions ofchairman and chief executive officer.   Mr. Ondaatje founded the securities firm in 1970, but soldhis stake three years ago to pursue publishing interests. Hisinvestment would have provided some muchneeded capital forthe money-losing company.   On the Toronto Stock Exchange yesterday, Loewen Ondaatjeshares closed at C$2.35, off 30 Canadian cents.</TEXT></DOC>